Writing an ls clone in Rust

6 steps

In this short tutorial, you learn how to build an ls clone in Rust. It will not cover all the features of the original ls core utility for Unix and Unix-like systems and we won't guarantee that the output matches the original core utility. However, this tutorial will teach you how to use the existing standard library in Rust to interact with your filesystem.

Let's start learning!

For technical help on the StackUp platform & tutorial-related questions, join our Discord, to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Recommended to have finished Speedrun Rust.
  • Recommended to have finished Rust Basics.
  • A working Rust installation. For instructions, head to https://rustup.rs/ and follow the platform-specific instructions.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Present file and directory information as a utility
  • Perform file system interaction on a Unix/Unix-like operating system
  • Learn some functionalities from the fs and env modules from the standard library

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: Preparing The Project

    Before proceeding, ensure that you have Rust installed on your Linux operating system. If you don't have any Linux or MacOS machine, you can always use GitHub Codespaces.

    Once Rust is installed (see prerequisites), run the following command on your terminal.

    cargo new lister

    The version of Rust in this tutorial is 1.85.1 with Rust edition 2024. Ensure that you have at least version 1.85.

    This will create a new Rust project with a root directory called lister. Head to the lister directory. Run the following command.

    cargo run

    This should give an output on the terminal "Hello, world!". If so, this means the project was generated correctly. In the next step, let's discuss what kind of features we are going to have with this project.

  • Step 2: Writing A Simple Software Architectural Documentation

    Software architectural documentation is a set of documents that describe the architecture of a software system. It provides an in-depth understanding of how the software is structured and how its components interact with each other. This documentation serves as a blueprint for the system's design, development, deployment, and maintenance.

    Although this project does not actually need it, this step guides you through the thought process of writing a software architectural documentation.

    In a typical project, there are simple guide questions that help break down a problem into several sub-problems.

    Each sub-problem can be further divided into smaller sub-problems and so on. This makes it easier to manage and write solutions for each problem.

    To help break a problem into several sub-problems, there are some guide questions or steps that are usually followed or similar:

    1. What is the problem?

    2. What are the sub-problems?

    3. Are there already implemented solutions for these sub-problems? If so, what are they? If not, how do we solve it?

    4. Are we actually meeting the goals of the project? If so, proceed, otherwise, let's reassess.

    5. Repeat.

    These questions actually help build the requirements of a project, therefore, they can also help write a software architectural documentation.

    For now, our goals of our project are to

    • List files and directories
    • Output more information such as file size and inode numbers

    This project is small but it is still enough for a good exercise to write a software architectural documentation. Want to try out writing one by adding more features than what was previously mentioned?

    Create a new file called ARCHITECTURE.md and write along your own software architectural documentation or SA documentation, then share yours with our Discord server and let's see if there are differences and similarities between you and other fellow developers.

    Here is a sample ARCHITECTURE.md for this tutorial. You can paste this to https://gist.github.com to render the mermaid diagram as well. Click this link for what the full render looks like.

    # Software Architectural Documentation

This document details different components of the code base. The intention is to provide
a simple to explain but a high-level description of the projects goals and plans
to each of these internal mechanisms.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
ls["ls clone"]
f[files]
d[directories]
ls -. lists .- f 
ls -. lists .- d 
ls -. lists .- b["both files and directories"]
ls -- can list --> w["inside a specified directory"]
f -- other information that can be shown is --> metadata
f -- other information that can be shown is --> fs["file size"]
f -- other information that can be shown is --> fe["inode number"]
```

## CLI
Since this clone project is just an attempt to have similar functionality to the original,
it's also a command line tool or a command line interface (CLI).

A CLI is a frontend for running internal code behind the scenes, much like a webpage which
runs internal code using the web browser.

## Features

This project features the ability to list files and directories. Users can specify directories as well to list what's inside.
It can also output extra information such as file size and inode number.
    Markdown
  • Step 3: Listing Files and Directories

    Ensure that you are still inside the root directory of the project which is the lister directory. Edit the file src/main.rs and write the following code that imports the following modules to the current namespace.

    use std::env;
use std::fs;
    Rust

    This code adds the env and fs modules from the standard library.

    The env module is important to get or manipulate information from the process's environment. This includes the current directory, environmental variables and additional command line arguments.

    The fs module contains file system manipulations such as copying files and directories from a source to a target destination.

    Next, write your code so that the file looks like the code block below.

    use std::env;
use std::fs;

fn main() {
    let current_directory = env::current_dir().unwrap();
    println!("{}", current_directory.display());
}
    Rust

    Save the file. Run the following command on your terminal.

    cargo run

    You should get a similar output like the screenshot below.

    It should print out the full path of the current directory of where the command was invoked.

    Write your code so that the file looks like the code block below.

    use std::env;
use std::fs;

fn main() {
    let current_directory = env::current_dir().unwrap();
    println!("{}", current_directory.display());
    for entry in current_directory
        .read_dir()
        .expect("Unable to read directory.")
    {
        let entry = entry.unwrap();
        let entry = entry.path();
        println!("{}", entry.display());
    }
}
    Rust

    Save the file. Run the following command on your terminal.

    cargo run

    You should get a similar output like the screenshot below.

    For now, it will print out the full absolute path to the current directory. In the next step, let's try adding a feature that allows lister to list if a directory or directories are specified.

  • Step 4: Listing Inside Directories

    The program currently lists only files and directories within the directory where the program was invoked.

    We want it to list directories that are specified as additional command line arguments, but we have to ensure that the command line arguments are parsed correctly.

    Write this code and replace the contents with it to your main.rs file. Keep a close eye to line 7 since this contains code that prints additional arguments

    use std::env;
use std::fs;

fn main() {
    let additional_args = env::args();
    // The first argument is the path of the executable
    println!("{:?}", additional_args);
    let current_directory = env::current_dir().unwrap();
    println!("{}", current_directory.display());
    for entry in current_directory
        .read_dir()
        .expect("Unable to read directory.")
    {
        let entry = entry.unwrap();
        let entry = entry.path();
        println!("{}", entry.display());
    }
}
    Rust

    Save the file. Run the following command.

    cargo run

    Your output should look similar to the screenshot below.

    For those unfamiliar, they might think that the first argument should be run since it is an additional command line argument for cargo. But alas, it is not, it will be the compiled executable. This is because according to Rust documentation for the env::args(),

    The first element is traditionally the path of the executable, but it can be set to arbitrary text, and might not even exist. This means this property should not be relied upon for security purposes.
    -

    To avoid such confusion, you might want to run the following commands instead of the previous invocation.

    cargo build
./target/debug/lister

    This ensures that you know the second command ./target/debug/lister is the executable and not cargo. This also helps prevent confusion when we are going to handle additional command line arguments.

    Run the following command on your terminal.

    ./target/debug/lister additional command line arguments

    Your output should now contain text like the one below.

    Args { inner: ["./target/debug/lister", "additional", "command", "line", "arguments"] }

    Since the name or path to the executable is the first element, therefore, we should check if there are elements at index greater than 0. With this knowledge, we can make additional arguments as specified directory names inside the current working directory.

    Write the following code to replace the contents of src/main.rs.

    use std::env;
use std::fs;
use std::path::Path;

fn main() {
    let additional_args: Vec<String> = env::args().collect();
    // The first argument is the path of the executable
    let current_directory = env::current_dir().unwrap();
    if additional_args.len() < 2 {
        for entry in current_directory
            .read_dir()
            .expect("Unable to read directory.")
        {
            let entry = entry.unwrap();
            let entry = entry.path();
            println!("{}", entry.display());
        }
    } else {
        for index in 1..additional_args.len() {
            let new_path = Path::new(&additional_args[index]);
            for entry in new_path.read_dir().expect("Unable to read directory.") {
                let entry = entry.unwrap();
                let entry = entry.path();
                println!("{}", entry.display());
            }
        }
    }
}
    Rust

    Run the following command.

    cargo build

    Now test your new executable. The screenshot below should be enough to know how to test your new executable.

    As shown in the screenshot above, if a directory name does not exist, the command fails and panics. Another issue is also passing file names, thus, running read_dir on a file causes a panic like the screenshot below.

    To solve the issue when passing a file, we can improve our code ensuring that the arguments are actual paths and check also that it is either a file or a directory. Here is the full code of one such solution with added error handling. Write this code to replace the contents of your src/main.rs file.

    use std::env;
use std::fs;
use std::io::Result;
use std::path::Path;

fn lister(path: &Path) -> Result<()> {
    // We can just output it as text if it's a file
    if path.is_file() {
        println!("{}", path.display());
    } else {
        for entry in path.read_dir().expect("Unable to read directory.") {
            let entry = entry.unwrap();
            let entry = entry.path();
            println!("{}", entry.display());
        }
    }
    Ok(())
}

fn main() -> Result<()> {
    let additional_args: Vec<String> = env::args().collect();
    // The first argument is the path of the executable
    let current_directory = env::current_dir().unwrap();
    if additional_args.len() < 2 {
        lister(&current_directory)?;
    } else {
        for entry in 1..additional_args.len() {
            let path = Path::new(&additional_args[entry]);
            lister(&path)?;
        }
    }
    Ok(())
}
    Rust

    If a directory or file does not exist, the code preserves the panic behaviour.

  • Step 5: Including File and Directory Metadata

    In this step, we add the ability to output metadata such as file or directory size, and inode number.

    We can do so by using the fs module from the standard library and output such information. Replace the lister function in src/main.rs with the following code below.

    fn lister(path: &Path) -> Result<()> {
    // We can just output it as text if it's a file
    if path.is_file() {
        let metadata = fs::metadata(&path)?;
        println!(
            "Kind: File\t{}\t{} bytes\t{}",
            path.display(),
            metadata.size(),
            metadata.ino()
        );
    } else {
        for entry in path.read_dir().expect("Unable to read directory.") {
            let entry = entry.unwrap();
            let entry = entry.path();
            let metadata = fs::metadata(&entry)?;
            println!(
                "Kind: Directory\t{}\t{} bytes\t{}",
                entry.display(),
                metadata.size(),
                metadata.ino()
            );
        }
    }
    Ok(())
}
    Rust

    Run the following commands.

    cargo clean
cargo build

    Finally, run the following command to check the new output.

    ./target/debug/lister target src Cargo.toml

    Your output should look similar to the screenshot below.

    You can see how easy it is to use the fs::metadata() function in Rust. It's a very useful utility to output metadata such as size in bytes and inode number.

    Now try adding other information on your own and share yours on our Discord server.

  • Step 6: Stacking It Up!

    Congratulations on finishing this short tutorial! You have learned the basics on how to get command line arguments, pass them as values to be processed and validated as paths, and use them to list files and directories, and even output more information such as size and inode number.
